\begin_layout Section
Background Information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF) works to make digital
 biodiversity data openly and freely available on the internet for everyone.
 GBIF provides access to scientific biodiversity data for decision-making,
 research endeavours and public use.
 GBIF endorses both open source software and open data access.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of structure, GBIF is a dynamic, growing partnership of countries,
 organisations, institutions and individuals working together to mobilise
 scientific biodiversity data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
GBIF is also a network of data publishers who retain ownership and control
 of the data they share.
 Linked datasets provide a more robust representation of biodiversity than
 any single dataset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this framework, GBIF develops software tools to make it possible to easily
 integrate biodiversity data from heterogeneous sources using common standards
 and protocols.
 One of these tools is the GBIF Integrated Publishing Toolkit (IPT) that
 this user manual refers to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GBIF IPT is an open source, Java (TM) based web application that connects
 and serves three types of biodiversity data: taxon primary occurrence data,
 taxon checklists and general resource metadata.
 The data registered in a GBIF IPT instance is connected to the GBIF distributed
 network and made available for public consultation and use.
 Several factors have motivated the development of this new tool: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the limitations of the existing systems to publish primary biodiversity
 occurrence records that use tools and protocols that were not designed
 to transfer big amounts of records (DiGIR, TAPIR, ABCD); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the need to decentralise and speed up the process of indexing biodiversity
 occurrence datasets; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the need to offer additional benefits and services to the data publishers
 to encourage data publication (i.e.
 public web interface to browse/expose (meta)data or mapping services);
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the need to offer data quality assessment tools to data publishers and to
 generalise data cleaning habits; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the need to increase data exchange using globally accepted formats (i.e.
 OGC web services); 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the need for easy ways to monitor data access and use for the different
 resources connected to the GBIF Network; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the lack of appropriate tools to publish certain types of biodiversity data,
 such as names checklists and dataset metadata; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
existing requests to facilitate and automate dataset registration with the
 GBIF network; 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the requirement to implement (and assign if needed) Universal Unique Identifiers
 (UUIDs) associated to all published elements to increase interoperability
 in the GBIF Network; 
\end_layout

