\begin_layout Subsubsection
Taxon Primary Occurrence Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taxon Primary Occurrence Data (or simply, occurrence data) is defined in
 the scope of GBIF as digital text or multimedia data record detailing facts
 about the instance of occurrence of an organism, i.e.
 on the what, where, when, how and by whom of the occurrence and the recording.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In terms of connecting data to the IPT, an occurrence dataset is defined
 as a table or database storing information about the distribution of biological
 organisms in the form of points defined by a textual description and/or
 geographical coordinates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Taxonomic Checklists
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taxonomic checklist data refers to structured data providing information
 about taxonomic names and their relationships.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Resource Metadata
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of GBIF, metadata records are those which provide information
 about the suppliers of biodiversity data and about the origins and purpose
 of those data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As regards the IPT, a metadata record is composed of all the descriptive
 information that must be attached to a dataset in terms of origin (who
 produced the original data, who is connecting it to the IPT instance),
 contents (both taxonomically and geographically), intellectual property
 rights, etc.
\end_layout

